    "recap_headline": "Eastern Michigan Athletics",
    "recap_text": "Photo Gallery\n|\nRe-Watch the Game\n|\nLate Inning Highlights\nYPSILANTI, Mich. (EMUEagles.com) \u2013\nThe Eastern Michigan University baseball team earned its first Mid-American Conference victory of the season in dramatic fashion Saturday, March 21, securing a 9-8 walk-off victory in 10 innings against the University of Akron at Oestrike Stadium.\nThe win marked the first MAC win in the Interim Head Coach\nTrevor Beerman\nera (2026-present).\nEastern secured the win by scoring six runs in the final four innings highlighted by\nDevan Zirwas'\n(Imperial, Pa./West Allegheny/VCU)\ngame-tying two-run homer in the ninth to force extra innings. Eastern won the game off a bases-loaded hit by pitch from\nTJ Williams\n(Racine, Wis./Racine Horlick/Kansas)\nto end the contest in a 9-8 final.\nEastern sophomore\nFischer Hendershot\n(Flushing, Mich./Flint Powers)\n(1-1)\nearned his first win of the season on the mound as he tossed a scoreless 0.2 innings. Akron's Garrett Groce (0-2) was tagged with the loss.\nHow it Happened\nEastern Michigan jumped out to an early 3-0 lead in the third inning. Zirwas ignited the offense with a two-run triple to right field, and\nBruce Jellison\n(Hartland, Mich./Hartland/Wabash Valley)\nfollowed with an RBI groundout to extend the advantage.\nThe lead was short-lived, as Akron erupted for seven runs in the top of the fifth inning. The Zips capitalized on five hits, multiple walks and a costly EMU error to seize a 7-3 lead. The Eagles began to chip away in the seventh, loading the bases and scoring three runs on RBIs from\nKevin Krill\n(White Lake, Mich./Lakeland/Oakland/Kalamazoo Valley C.C.)\n,\nJohn Hale\n(Ashland City, Tenn./Sycamore/Motlow State C.C.)\n, and a walk by\nNathan Borchardt\n(Stanley, N.C./East Lincoln/King)\nto cut the deficit to 7-6.\nAfter Akron added an insurance run in the top of the ninth to make it 8-6, Zirwas delivered the game's most pivotal swing. With two outs, he launched a towering two-run home run to tie the game and send it to extra innings. In the bottom of the 10th, the Eagles loaded the bases and Williams was hit by a pitch to force in the winning run, completing the comeback.\nGame Notes\n\u00bb Eastern's record improved to 5-17 (1-7 MAC), and Akron's fell to 10-11 (4-4 MAC).\n\u00bb Eastern played its second extra-innings contest of the season, securing its first win in such games. It previously went to extras at Austin Peay, Feb. 21, losing, 8-7. It marked the first walk-off win for the team since it walked off Kent State in 12 innings, 12-11, May 15, 2025.\n\u00bb The Eagles recorded 13 total hits, their fifth time with double-digit hits this season. Eastern out-hit its opponent for the fifth time this season with 13 hits to Akron's 11. It moved to 2-3 when outhitting opponents.\n\u00bb Eastern worked eight walks and drove in nine runs, both of which are the second most for EMU in one game this season.\n\u00bb\nDevan Zirwas\nhit his eighth home run of the season in the form of a two-out game-tying shot in the bottom of the ninth. The eight homers match his total from last season and rank second in the MAC. He drove in four runs, tying his career high set against Ball State, March 15, the most from an individual Eagle in one game this season. Zirwas recorded one triple and one homer in the game, elevating his extra-base hit total to a team-high 15.\n\u00bb\nDevan\nZirwas\nlogged his seventh total multi-RBI game of the season, knocking in four runs. Zirwas leads the squad in RBIs, totaling 25 on the season.\n\u00bb\nTJ Williams\nsecured his team-best eighth multi-hit game of the season with a 2-for-6 showing at the dish. He has knocked at least two hits in three of his last four games.\n\u00bb\nDemir Heidelberg\n(Homewood, Ill./Homewood Flossmor)\nrecorded the third multi-hit game of his freshman campaign. This marks the first time in his career with back-to-back multi-hit performances. He extended his hitting streak to four straight games, a career-long streak.\n\u00bb\nJohn Hale\n(Ashland City, Tenn./Sycamore/Motlow State)\nhad two hits, which marked his fourth multi-hit game of the season, and 18th as an Eagle. In addition, he knocked in his 10th RBI of the season.\n\u00bb\nBruce Jellison\nreached base for the eighth consecutive game, which is currently the longest streak on the team. He had one hit and one RBI to bring his totals to nine hits and six RBI.\n\u00bb\nTommy Rose\n(Plymouth, Mich./Plymouth)\ntossed at least three innings for the fourth time this season. He allowed zero runs for the first time in his career.\n\u00bb\nAidan Norris\n(Platte City, Mo./Platte County)\ntossed his fourth scoreless appearance of the season, marking his third consecutive scoreless outing.\n\u00bb\nFischer Hendershot\nearned his first win of the season on the mound as he tossed a scoreless 0.2 innings.\nHistorical Notes\n\u00bb Interim Head Coach\nTrevor Beerman\nearned his first home and Mid-American Conference win.\n\u00bb Eastern won for the first time on the new field at Oestrike Stadium.\n\u00bb The Eagles met Akron for the 79th time. Eastern holds a 49-30 record all-time against the Zips and an 11-14 mark when facing it at Oestrike Stadium since 1999.\nUp Next\nThe Eagles and Zips will play again tomorrow, March 22, 12 p.m. for the rubber match of the series.\nFollow Us\nKeep up with all things Eastern baseball by following the team on X\n@EMU_Baseball\n, and on Instagram\n@emu_baseball\n.",
